(138, 1, '2024-04-10 15:15:19', '2024-04-10 15:15:19', 'Malitbog, officially designated as the Municipality of Malitbog (Banuwa ta Malitbog in Bukid and Higaonon; Lungsod sa Malitbog in Cebuano; Bayan ng Malitbog in Tagalog), holds the status of a 2nd class municipality within the province of Bukidnon, Philippines. According to the 2020 census, it boasts a population of 26,741 people. The history of Malitbog traces back to a group of pioneers from the Bukidnon tribe who initially settled along a spring called Abo-on. As their numbers increased, the area was named Abo-on, but due to its limited representation of the whole settlement, the name was eventually changed to Malitbog, inspired by the Malitbog River that traversed the settlement—a vital source for fishing, the community’s primary livelihood.\n\nOn June 25, 1963, through Executive Order No. 42, Malitbog attained the status of a 5th Class municipality, marking its transition into a regular municipality by the operation of Republic Act 1515, and acknowledged under Republic Acts 23 and 88, duly signed by President Diosdado Macapagal.\n\nGeographically, Malitbog is situated at the northernmost part of Bukidnon, with specific coordinates between parallel 8°25’35” and 8°36’8″ North Latitude and Meridians 124°49’39” and 125°11’39” East Longitude. Bounded by the municipalities of Claveria and Tagoloan to the north, Manolo Fortich and Impasugong to the south, and Esperanza in Agusan del Sur to the east, Malitbog is approximately 40 kilometers from the regional capital, Cagayan de Oro, and a 2½-hour ride from the provincial capital, Malaybalay City.\n\nMalitbog is politically subdivided into 11 barangays, each with its own unique characteristics and land area. San Luis is the largest barangay, covering about 66.8 percent of Malitbog’s total land area, while Poblacion is the smallest, representing only 1.14 percent of the municipality’s area coverage.\n\nThe climate in Malitbog is categorized as Type IV or Intermediate B, typical of the province, characterized by a moderate season from February to April and a wet season starting from May, lasting up to January.', '7', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', '7-3', '', '', '2024-04-10 15:17:50', '2024-04-10 15:17:50', '', 9, 'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/7.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
