(141, 1, '2024-04-10 15:22:06', '2024-04-10 15:22:06', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"800\"}},\"fontSize\":\"large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-large-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:800\">Brief Historical Background</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As early as 1700 people in this town were already living in clusters but this place has no name yet. This group of people were headed by a Datu whom they have chosen to be the most qualified to the position. This Datu had right hand men known by the name of Amay Mantumbaga, Amay Kagang-kagang and Amay Guinaya. Due to the superior abilities of this Datu and his three right hand men, a Muslim datu came to make friends with them. As a token of their friendship, the Muslim gave them a very big agong called “Agong Makatukag”. Once the sound of this agong was heard, immediately the people would assemble in the house of their Datu. This Muslim Datu was the very one who baptized their Datu to the name Datu Saguilongan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Years passed and the people worked hard and lived in plentiful. They had wide ricefields. People from the neighboring places along the beach come up during the harvest season to help harvest the rice. They did not stay long so the people immediately returned to their homes, happy as ever.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Datu Saguilongan had many children but had only one daughter whom he loved so dearly. One day he told his daughter, “ My dear, if ever you will marry, please don’t marry a stranger.” A stranger might be a spy of the spaniards who will come and drive us out our homes.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One harvest season, many harvesters came. Among the group was a tall handsome young man who happened to love the Datu’s Daughter. She was restricted to talk to the visitor but when the woman fetch water, the young man would follow her to the spring and there they had a chance to converse together. After a few weeks, the datu’s daughter fell in love with the stranger. This relation between the two was not known by her father since he was out often times. After the harvest season, the harvesters went home.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The suitor of the Datu’s Daughter came every now and then for a visit, so that Datu knew of the relation of his daughter to the stranger. He was very, very angry and he severely scolded his daughter. He drove the stranger away. As her punishment, she was locked in one of the rooms of their house and restricted to go out. She was closely guarded.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At this moment, his daughter grieved so much and refused to eat and last she became sick. One day, her mother pities her, so she opened the door when the stranger came for visit. They planned to elope, but was impossible. They did not talk so loud because the Datu came home and scolded her daughter once more severely. She was locked again in her home. From this time on, his daughter became serious and finally became mentally upset. She could not sleep and refused to eat.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, the Datu called for Amay Mantumbaga, Amay Kagang-Kagang and Amay Guinaya begging them to help him cure his sick daughter. He promised a reward to anyone who can cure her. The Datu’s problem became a problem to all his people.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is so happened that one day, they failed to lock the door. His daughter escaped and nowhere to be found. Everyone searched for for here and there, but she could not be found. At last, her suitor came and helped in the search. He thought of going to the spring where they used to meet. Right in the middle of the river was a big stone. There sat a woman looking the spring. He called for her and when she heard her lover’s call, she stood up and looked to be well and her normal mind. Rastily, the young man went to rescue her, he lifted and carried her down the stone to the river and carried the two down, down to the river.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Many people ran to the bank to witnessed the happening. They told the Datu everything. The Datu and his wife cried. The Datu repented why he had restricted his only daughter too much in the wrong way. He beat and beat his agong and so his people came. He ordered them to look for the dead bodies of the two, but never could be found. He related the cause of the death of his only daughter. “Nalibog, Nalibog”. This is the dialect meaning- a person becomes insane. The Datu repented for all what he had done, but it’s useless after all.” Therefore, the Datu can never undone.” Repentance always come late. Therefore, the Datu told his people, “ let us call our town Malibog, so I will never forget my only daughter.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This went on hand of datu Saguilongan’s son Roberto by name succeeded him. This old man headed the town for many years. An American Superintended by the name of Mr. Khenly came and promised the people to open a school if there will be a school site. Immediately, Captain Roberto Saguilongan donated the 18 hectares as a school site. Most likely in the Deed Donation, it was registered as Malitbog, Instead of Malibog. After his death, Captain Mayong Doroteo Kilem by name became next captain and headed the town for many, many years.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From this story, you will not that the founders of this town of Malitbog are the Saguilongans and Kilems family. What Malitbog is of today, now is possible and owed from two families mentioned above.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'About', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '9-revision-v1', '', '', '20